can Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and Dutch: occupational name for a baker of bread, or brick and tiles, derived from Middle High German and Middle Dutch <i>backen</i> ‘to bake’. The German surname is also found in France (mainly Lorraine and Alsace).","Danish: occupational name for a baker, from <i>bechere</i> ‘baker’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a baker, from German <i>Bäcker</i> (compare 1 and   Backer  ) or Yiddish <i>beker</i> ‘baker’."],"variants":[{"name":"Backer","meanings":["German (<b>Bäcker</b>): variant of   Becker  . Compare   Baecker  .","Dutch: variant of   Bakker  . Compare   De Backer  .","Danish: probably of German origin (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Beckers","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ewald, Gerda, Hans, Klaus, Kurt, Wendelin, Wilhelmina.  French Jacques, Thierry.","Dutch, Flemish, and German: variant of   Becker   + the genitive case <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Baecker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegfried, Bodo, Gerhardt, Heinz, Horst, Kurt, Waltraud.","German (mainly <b>Bäcker</b>): variant of   Becker  . Compare   Backer  ."]},{"name":"Beck","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from northern Middle English <i>bekke</i> ‘stream’ (Old Norse <i>bekkr</i>).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of various places in northern France named Bec, for example Bec Hellouin in Eure, named with Old Norman French <i>bec</i> ‘stream’, from the same Old Norse root as in 1 above.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Becke</i> (Old English <i>Becca</i> or <i>Beocca</i>), of uncertain origin."]},{"name":"Beckerle","meanings":["South German: diminutive of   Becker  ."]},{"name":"De Beck","meanings":["Flemish: short form of <b>De Becker</b>, see   Becker  , or a variant of   Beckman  ."]},{"name":"Beckermann","meanings":["German: variant of   Becker   ‘baker’, formed with Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Mathis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian: learned doublet of   Mads ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathies","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]},{"name":"Matthias","meanings":["New Testament Greek form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i> (  see  Matthew  ), or rather of an Aramaic derivative. The Latin form of the name is <i>Matthaeus</i>. In English the form <i>Matthias</i> is used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament to distinguish the disciple who was chosen after the treachery of Judas to make up the twelve (Acts 1:23–26) from the evangelist <i>Matthew</i>. However, this distinction is not observed in other languages, where <i>Matthias</i> (or a version of it) is often a learned doublet existing alongside a vernacular derivative."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathis Becker was born about 1537, in Württemberg, Germany. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Mathis Becker."},"et":{"about 1537–":"umbes 1537–Surnud","1540–Female":"1540–Surnud","1572–Male":"1572–Surnud","1537–Male":"1537–Surnud","about 1537":"umbes 1537","1540":"1540","1572":"1572","about 1572":"umbes 1572","1537":"1537","Württemberg-Hohenzollern, Germany":"Baden-Württemberg, Saksamaa","Württember